    {
      "title": "The 4 Main Verb Conjugation Patterns",
      "text": "Most Slovak verbs follow one of four main conjugation patterns. These patterns are usually recognizable from the infinitive ending. The most important difference appears in the 3rd person plural (they form).",
      "examples": [
        "Pozerajú televíziu. – They watch TV.",
        "Hovoria po slovensky. – They speak Slovak.",
        "Študujú doma. – They study at home.",
        "Rozumejú tomu. – They understand it."
      ],
      "table": {
        "headers": ["Type", "Infinitive Example", "1sg", "2sg", "3sg", "1pl", "2pl", "3pl (key ending)"],
        "rows": [
          ["-ať (pozerat type)", "pozerať", "pozerám", "pozeráš", "pozerá", "pozeráme", "pozeráte", "pozerajú"],
          ["-iť (hovorit type)", "hovoriť", "hovorím", "hovoríš", "hovorí", "hovoríme", "hovoríte", "hovoria"],
          ["-ovať (studovat type)", "študovať", "študujem", "študuješ", "študuje", "študujeme", "študujete", "študujú"],
          ["-ieť (rozumiet type)", "rozumieť", "rozumiem", "rozumieš", "rozumie", "rozumieme", "rozumiete", "rozumejú"]
        ]
      }
    },

    {
      "title": "How to Recognize the 3rd Person Plural",
      "text": "The easiest way to classify Slovak verbs is by looking at their 3rd person plural form. Each verb group has a typical ending.",
      "examples": [
        "-ajú → pozerať → pozerajú",
        "-ia → hovoriť → hovoria",
        "-ujú → študovať → študujú",
        "-ejú → rozumieť → rozumejú"
      ],
      "table": {
        "headers": ["Verb Type", "3rd Person Plural Ending", "Example"],
        "rows": [
